# UI/UX Design rules

## Layout & spacing

- Use a consistent spacing scale from tokens (`--spacing-1` through `--spacing-12` or similar). Never arbitrary values.
- Align elements to a grid. Prefer multiples of 4px or 8px.
- Use whitespace intentionally — group related items closer, unrelated items further apart (proximity principle).
- Content max-width: constrain readable text to ~65–75ch. Never let a text block span the full viewport on wide screens.

## Typography

- Maximum 2 typefaces per project (one for headings, one for body). Usually one is enough.
- Type scale: define sizes as tokens (`--text-sm`, `--text-base`, `--text-lg`, `--text-xl`, `--text-2xl`). No arbitrary font sizes.
- Body line-height: 1.5–1.6. Heading line-height: 1.1–1.3.
- Never use `font-weight` below 400 for body text. 500–700 for emphasis.

## Color

- Define a semantic color system: `--color-primary`, `--color-surface`, `--color-text-primary`, `--color-text-muted`, `--color-border`, `--color-error`, `--color-success`.
- Never use raw hex in components — always a token.
- Ensure WCAG AA contrast: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text and UI components.
- Do not rely on color alone to convey meaning — pair with icon, label, or pattern.

## Components

- Every interactive element must have: default, hover, focus-visible, active, and disabled states.
- Focus ring must always be visible — never remove `outline` without a custom replacement.
- Touch targets minimum 44×44px on mobile.
- Destructive actions (delete, reset) must require confirmation and be visually distinct (red/warning color).

## Feedback & states

- Every async action needs: loading indicator, success confirmation, and error message.
- Empty states must explain what the space is for and offer a clear action (e.g. "No titles yet — Add your first title").
- Error messages must tell the user what went wrong and what to do — not just "Something went wrong".

## Motion

- Prefer subtle transitions (150–250ms, ease-out) for state changes (hover, open/close).
- No animation purely for decoration. Motion must aid comprehension (entrance, exit, state change).
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` — wrap non-essential animations in `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)`.

## Responsive

- Mobile-first. Design the mobile layout first, then expand for tablet and desktop.
- Test at 320px, 768px, and 1280px minimum.
- No horizontal scroll at any standard breakpoint.
- Tap targets and form inputs must be at least 44px tall on mobile.

## Accessibility

- Semantic HTML first — `button` for actions, `a` for navigation, `nav`/`main`/`section` landmarks.
- All images need meaningful `alt` or `alt=""` if decorative.
- Form inputs must have associated `<label>` elements — not just placeholder text.
- Check color contrast before shipping any new UI.
